but albumartistsort. So rename it and use the proper name.

Because they are integer fields, they require special convertion. Might
as well properly map them and use human-understandable names.

commit.message: Update docs

Update translations

This is just the result of running `update_translations.py`. For the
most part only the source lines change. Only the afr and es_ES ones
change for real, because they haven't been updated in a while since
they were missing from the .pro file.

Also ran `lrelease` to update the `.qm` files, where also only afr and
es_ES had any changes.

Move translations

There is a slight name clash since there already is a `translations.py`,
but since this is just a folder and not a package it should be fine.

This also includes two fixes: afr was missing in the .pro file, so it
wasn't updated by the update_translation.py script. And the unused and
practically empty es_es translation is removed, in favour of the better
and already used es_ES one.

Migrate translations

They also get their own prefix, and require the same `./` workaround as
config data for the same reason: path-foo. Right now they reside outside
`puddlestuff` package, that will be fixed soon.

Migrate icons

I could re-use the `data` prefix, but opted to use a dedicated `icons`
prefix in preparation for when we ever get around to restructure the
`data` directory. We don't need the `./` here since there is no path-foo
done.

Migrate config data

The config files here use the superfluous `./` in the path. The reason
for that is that puddletag does some path-magic using `os.path` which
relies on the fact that the path of the resource have a `/` right before
the actual filename. I don't want to touch that right now, so using this
workaround to keep it working for now.

Also remove the old ini-style and by now unused puddletag.conf.

Prepare resource.py

The idea is to basically implement the solution suggested here [0]. By
putting the search path additions in the existing `resource.py`, it acts
as a kind of drop-in replacement: if you import that, you will be able
to access the resources using their prefix and path.

[0] https://stackoverflow.com/a/66104687/1094486
